                                Report abuseTranscript of Philip H. Knight Philip H. Knight University of OregonWhile Knight was at the University of Oregon,  he met and trained as a middle-distance runner with the legendary track coach Bill Bowerman. Knights nickname was Buck, and although he was known more for his enthusiasm than his natural running talent, he struck up an immediate friendship with Bowerman.  Bowerman was determined to wear the best shoes possible, Knight became his guinea pig when it came to trying out new shoes. Bowerman was not satisfied with any shoes they tried and started designing his own shoes. n 1959, Knight graduated from Oregon with a degree in journalism. He had been an indifferent student and, still not knowing what to do with his life, Knight enlisted in the army. After completing a year of service, Knight decided to enroll in the Graduate School of Business at Stanford University. Stanford Finally, at Stanford, Knight actually began to enjoy school and learning about something other than sports. His favorite class soon became a business class. The teacher  had gave his students an assignment in which they had to invent a new business, describe its purpose, and create a marketing plan. Knights paper was called, Can Japanese Sports Shoes Do to German Sports Shoes What Japanese Cameras Did to German Cameras? In it, Knight developed a blueprint for superior athletic shoes, which could be produced cheaply in Japan. Despite having found his true calling, Knight ended up doing what his fathers wanted and took up a real job with a Portland-based accounting firm after graduating from Stanford. He didn't last long there, later on he took his business plan to Japan. Japan In 1962, Knight flew to Japan to visit Onitsuka Tiger Co., manufacturer of an Adidas knockoff sold in Japan. Introducing himself as the head of Blue Ribbon Sports, a company which did not exist yet.  They ended up sending him samples which caused him to have to borrow money from his father. He sent a few pairs to his former University of Oregon coach, Bill Bowerman, who quickly became his partner. Knight began selling from his car at high school track meets throughout the Pacific Northwest.By the early 1970s, Blue Ribbon  went solo and start designing its own shoes. In 1972, Blue Ribbon launched its Nike line, named after the Greek goddess of victory. Emblazoned with a "swoosh" logo Knight paid a Portland State art student $35 to design, the shoes featured a unique "waffle sole"-created by Bowerman-that offered better traction with less weight.Conclusion By 1986, total sales hit $1 billion, and Nike surpassed Adidas to become the No. 1 shoe manufacturer worldwide. Between 1986 and 1987, Nike sales dropped 18 percent. Knight was forced to face the fact that while Nike technology appealed to sports professionals, other consumers might rank appearance over function. In response, Nike came up with Nike Air-a multipurpose shoe with an air cushion in the sole. But as Nike has grown into a huge multinational enterprise, it has become a magnet for controversy. Philip Knight, now in his late 50s, has come to be viewed as one of the master marketers of the age. ChildhoodPhilip was born on February 24, 1938, in Portland, Oregon.  Philip H. Knight was the son of Lota Hatfield Knight and William W. Knight. He discovered his love for running at a young age, and was a key member of the track team at Cleveland High School. From there, Knight moved on to the University of Oregon, where he found himself competing with Olympic distance runners. OlympicsKnight decided to get top athletes to endorse his shoes, and then let his sales force sell the product. That summer, the Olympic track and field trials were held in Eugene, Oregon, with none other than Bill Bowerman as coach of the American Olympic team. Knight put Nikes on the feet of several top finishers. When they made national television, so did the shoes they were wearing. One of the most visible runners to wear Nikes was American record-holder Steve Prefontaine. Full transcriptMore presentations by
    
        
